<HiddenGrammarLayout
  title="Art Lab"
  description="Structured tools for looking at art — grounded in what's visually observable, not in what the art world has decided it means."
>
  <div class="hg-page">

    <!-- ── TOP: INTRO + SIDEBAR ────────────────────────────── -->
    <div class="al-body">

      <!-- Left: intro content -->
      <div class="al-intro">
        <h1 class="al-intro-title">Art Lab</h1>

        <!-- Origin story -->
        <p class="al-intro-body">I talk to myself when I make art. Always have.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">Not out loud—through materials. The way a mark lands or doesn't. The decision to scrape something back, or let it stay. It's a conversation with an idea I'm trying to get out of my head and onto a surface.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">Making art does what voice-to-text does. The internal thing—the feeling, the image, the half-formed thought—goes through a translation. Materials. Surface. Process. And somewhere in that translation, things get lost. Or distorted. Or what you thought came through didn't.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">The artist usually can't see this. You're too close to the original intention. You know what you meant, so you read it back in. The curse of knowledge. You believe the idea is on the surface because you can still feel it in your chest.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">Then you show the work to someone. There's a silence. Or polite confusion. Or feedback that tells you they saw something completely different—not wrong, exactly, but nowhere near what you were reaching for.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">That's the gap. Art Lab makes it visible.</p>
        <a href="/hidden-grammar/why" class="al-text-link">Why I built this →</a>

        <!-- Art world + brain flags -->
        <div class="al-section-rule"></div>
        <p class="al-intro-body">The art world has its own idea of what success looks like. Price. Placement. Which galleries, which critics bother to show up. Art Lab is built around a different measure entirely: whether someone stands in front of your work long enough for something to happen to them.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">That's not random. It's not taste. It's not about whether the viewer is educated or the right kind of person. It comes down to specific decisions made in the studio—decisions that fire brain flags before the viewer has formed a single thought about the work. Before meaning. Before judgment. Before they decide whether they're the type of person who understands art.</p>
        <p class="al-intro-body">That's where the real levers are.</p>
        <a href="/hidden-grammar/grammar" class="al-text-link">How the visual grammar works →</a>

        <!-- Triage -->
        <div class="al-triage">
          <h2 class="al-triage-title">What are you here to do?</h2>
          <p class="al-triage-intro">Pick the one that fits. Each path surfaces the tools most relevant to what you're after.</p>
          <div class="al-triage-options">

            <div class="al-triage-option">
              <span class="al-triage-num">1</span>
              <div class="al-triage-content">
                <p class="al-triage-label">I'm making work and want to see my choices more clearly.</p>
                <p class="al-triage-desc">You're mid-process. Something's off, or you want to push further without polishing it into safety. The making tools are for you.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="al-triage-option">
              <span class="al-triage-num">2</span>
              <div class="al-triage-content">
                <p class="al-triage-label">I'm looking at a work—mine or someone else's—and want to understand what it's doing.</p>
                <p class="al-triage-desc">Finished work, yours or anyone else's. Structured reads grounded in what's visually observable, not in what the art world has decided it means.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="al-triage-option">
              <span class="al-triage-num">3</span>
              <div class="al-triage-content">
                <p class="al-triage-label">I'm helping other people look—teaching, leading a tour, explaining to someone who didn't ask.</p>
                <p class="al-triage-desc">Docent scripts, tour frameworks, wall text, educational critique. Something concrete to point at instead of art-speak.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

            <div class="al-triage-option">
              <span class="al-triage-num">4</span>
              <div class="al-triage-content">
                <p class="al-triage-label">I work in commercial illustration and design and need a diagnostic read.</p>
                <p class="al-triage-desc">The same brain flags that operate in fine art operate on a shelf. Commercial illustration, CPG packaging, brand visual language.</p>
              </div>
            </div>

          </div>
          <a href="/hidden-grammar/toolkit" class="hg-btn hg-btn--primary al-triage-cta">Start with the Toolkit →</a>
        </div>

        <!-- Caution -->
        <div class="al-caution">
          <h2 class="al-caution-title">One thing before you pick a tool</h2>
          <p class="al-caution-body">Art Lab makes things legible that were previously invisible. That's useful. It can also, if you're not careful, turn creating into a performance review.</p>
          <p class="al-caution-body">If you're here to see your choices more clearly—to tighten, strengthen, understand what's working—it's for you. But if creating is mostly about pleasure or flow or finding your way, be careful. Once you start measuring, it's hard to stop. The measuring can become the point.</p>
          <p class="al-caution-body">Some artists will call this reductive. They're not wrong—any analysis reduces a work. The question is whether what remains after the reduction is useful to you.</p>
          <a href="/hidden-grammar/analysis-worth" class="al-text-link al-caution-link">Does analysis destroy an artwork? The full answer →</a>
          <p class="al-caution-kicker">Know what you came for.</p>
        </div>

      </div>

      <!-- Right: sidebar -->
      <aside class="al-sidebar">

        <div class="al-sidebar-card al-sidebar-reading">
          <h2 class="al-sidebar-card-title">Reading</h2>
          <ul class="al-reading-list">
            <li><a href="/hidden-grammar/why" class="al-reading-link">Why I built this</a></li>
            <li><a href="/hidden-grammar/grammar" class="al-reading-link">How the visual grammar works</a></li>
            <li><a href="/hidden-grammar/score" class="al-reading-link">The score that actually matters</a></li>
            <li><a href="/hidden-grammar/analysis-worth" class="al-reading-link">Does analysis destroy an artwork?</a></li>
            <li><a href="/hidden-grammar/not-alone" class="al-reading-link">You were not alone</a></li>
          </ul>
        </div>

      </aside>

    </div>

    <!-- ── SECTION CARDS — full width below ──────────────── -->
    <div class="al-sections">
      <div class="al-sections-header">
        <h2 class="al-sections-title">What's in Art Lab</h2>
      </div>
      <div class="hg-grid al-sections-grid">
        {sections.map(section => (
          section.status === 'live' ? (
            <a href={section.href} class="hg-card al-section-card">
              <div class="al-card-top">
                <span class="hg-card-label">{section.label}</span>
              </div>
              <h3 class="hg-card-title">{section.title}</h3>
              <p class="hg-card-desc">{section.description}</p>
              <div class="al-card-footer">
                <span></span>
                <span class="al-card-arrow">→</span>
              </div>
            </a>
          ) : (
            <div class="hg-card al-section-card al-section-card--soon">
              <div class="al-card-top">
                <span class="hg-card-label">{section.label}</span>
                <span class="al-badge-soon">Coming soon</span>
              </div>
              <h3 class="hg-card-title">{section.title}</h3>
              <p class="hg-card-desc">{section.description}</p>
              <div class="al-card-footer">
                <span class="al-card-arrow-soon">{section.cta}</span>
              </div>
            </div>
          )
        ))}
      </div>
    </div>

  </div>
</HiddenGrammarLayout>

